&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration:underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Background&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: At the recommendation of the deparment chair, in 2023 I authored a textbook to be used to teach OPWL 535, &lt;em&gt;Principles of Adult Learning&lt;/em&gt;. As a part of my research lab, I had dedicated the previous 1.5 years to reviewing the literature that would contribute to this book: cognitive psychology, neuroscience, memory, information processing, behaviorism, social learning, etc. I completed v1.0 of the book to be used in teaching OPWL 535 for Fall 2023.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration:underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Book Description&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: This graduate-level book covers principles of adult learning from the fields of neuroscience and cognitive psychology. The book opens with several contextual chapters covering the relationship between learning and performance in organizations, the science of developing expertise, and considerations of neurodiversity, culture, and ethics. The bulk of the book is then organized according to the three fundamental dimensions of learning: cognitive, behavioral, and socio-emotional. There are four chapters dedicated to the cognitive dimension, covering the central nervous system, memory, neuroplasticity, metacognition, and learning through audio-visual channels via technology. There is one chapter dedicated to the behavioral dimension, focusing on highly behavioral performances. There are two chapters dedicated to the socio-emotional dimension, covering attitude, mindset, the role of emotion in the learning process, social constructivism, and social learning theory. The book ends with tactical chapters that discuss the key considerations for instructional designers (IDs) and learning experience designers (LXDs), and near-future trends. (Currently 211 pages.)&lt;/p&gt;
